 cultivate maize by combining these inputs with land and labor.
 Once harvested,
 a marketable surplus is sold to aggregators (often at the farm gate of in local markets),
 who transport the grain using bicycles or motorcycles to wholesalers or directly to large processors.
 Wholesalers generally sell to large processors.
 Farmers may also take part of the maize they consume themselves to small processors.
 Processors then transform the raw maize into final products,
 such as maize flour,
 which is distributed to retailers and ultimately purchased by consumers.
